gets into a fight in the Bronx.

00:31:15.110 --> 00:31:18.020
Do not screw up Sonja Sotomayor.

00:31:18.020 --> 00:31:20.940
But her office was so nice.

00:31:20.940 --> 00:31:23.270
They were so nice in
helping us get this right,

00:31:23.270 --> 00:31:24.830
and embarrassing
me with the details

00:31:24.830 --> 00:31:26.540
that I got wrong, of course.

00:31:26.540 --> 00:31:28.940
So this is -- I'm
going to read from one

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:32.220
of my favorite parts
of the book.

00:31:32.220 --> 00:31:34.570
And I also by the way, this
book is also the best use

00:31:34.570 --> 00:31:36.810
of Jewish guilt ever because
someone in my family --

00:31:36.810 --> 00:31:39.190
what we call in my family
Jewban, it's a Jewish Cuban.

00:31:39.190 --> 00:31:41.670
So she's Latina, and she's
like, if you don't do a book,

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:45.700
I'm going to murder you because
I have my little Latina niece

00:31:45.700 --> 00:31:47.000
and nephew.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.300
So this is it.

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:52.760
It says, "In my life, I was
the aji, the hot pepper,

00:31:52.760 --> 00:31:54.930
the one who wouldn't slow down.

00:31:54.930 --> 00:31:57.900
Because of where I was from,
because I was poor and Latina,

00:31:57.900 --> 00:32:00.420
some people didn't
think I would go far.

00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:03.460
But there were others who
helped my dreams come to life.

00:32:03.460 --> 00:32:07.030
They gave me opportunities
and reminded me to keep going.

00:32:07.030 --> 00:32:08.620
Those are the people
you need to listen to.

00:32:08.620 --> 00:32:11.270
Pay attention to the
ones who believe in you.

00:32:11.270 --> 00:32:13.830
The more you learn,
the farther you'll go.

00:32:13.830 --> 00:32:16.240
Education is a rocket ship.

00:32:16.240 --> 00:32:18.150
It can take you anywhere.

00:32:18.150 --> 00:32:22.910
But no matter how high you fly,
never forget where you started."

00:32:22.910 --> 00:32:24.210
And here's the final
page of the book.

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:26.350
It says, "Whether it's
in English, Spanish,

00:32:26.350 --> 00:32:30.260
or any other language, our
dreams are often the same:

00:32:30.260 --> 00:32:34.830
a loving family, kind friends,
a safe place to call home,

00:32:34.830 --> 00:32:37.450
and the chance to
reach our potential.

00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:40.050
The world outside your
window is a starting point,

00:32:40.050 --> 00:32:42.100
but there's so much
more beyond that.

00:32:42.100 --> 00:32:45.400
Read, study, do right by people.

00:32:45.400 --> 00:32:47.270
No matter where you're
born, there's no limit

00:32:47.270 --> 00:32:48.920
to what you can accomplish.

00:32:48.920 --> 00:32:50.950
I am Sonja Sotomayor.

00:32:50.950 --> 00:32:55.400
I am proud that with
opportunity comes justice."

00:32:55.400 --> 00:32:56.700
And there's the end of the book.

00:32:56.700 --> 00:32:58.500
I just ruined the
ending, by the way.

00:32:58.500 --> 00:33:02.160
[ Applause ]

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:03.660
That is the first time
anyone's heard the book.

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:04.960
This is actually,
like, a proof copy.

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:06.260
It's not even bound.

00:33:06.260 --> 00:33:07.560
You can, like, pull it apart.

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:09.560
But I felt like I knew what
you we're going to vote for.

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:11.760
Like, I'm from D.C. I'm like,
there's no way they're going

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:14.290
to be suckers and take the
book they can get in ten days.

00:33:14.290 --> 00:33:16.290
Like, this isn't coming
out until November.

00:33:16.290 --> 00:33:18.060
And plus, it's D.C., man.

00:33:18.060 --> 00:33:19.360
Supreme Court.

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:20.660
OK, other questions, yes?

00:33:20.660 --> 00:33:21.960
&gt;&gt; What's the age?

00:33:21.960 --> 00:33:23.260
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: Oh, sorry,

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:24.560
I never answered
your question, right.

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:25.860
[ Laughter ]

00:33:25.860 --> 00:33:27.160
Oh, screw your question.

00:33:27.160 --> 00:33:28.460
[ Laughter ]

00:33:28.460 --> 00:33:32.610
The age. So we are --
everyone is buying them

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:34.370
as baby gifts now, which
is fascinating to me.

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:36.580
They're building libraries of
real heroes for their kids,

00:33:36.580 --> 00:33:38.290
their grandkids, their
nieces and nephews.

00:33:38.290 --> 00:33:40.830
But our sweet spot is
actually 5 to 9 years old.

00:33:40.830 --> 00:33:43.220
If your kid's an early
reader, it's 4 to 9.

00:33:43.220 --> 00:33:45.160
But 5 to 9 is our sweet spot.

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:47.460
But thanks to everyone who's
bought all the baby gifts.

00:33:47.460 --> 00:33:48.760
It's amazing.

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:51.230
All these people now come to me
in line and they'll be pregnant

00:33:51.230 --> 00:33:53.610
or they'll say, my
granddaughter's pregnant,

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:55.580
and they'll say, you can't
tell anyone the name,

00:33:55.580 --> 00:33:56.920
and they whisper it to me.

00:33:56.920 --> 00:33:58.520
So I know everyone's
baby's first names before,

00:33:58.520 --> 00:33:59.820
like, the husbands do.

00:33:59.820 --> 00:34:01.120
[ Laughter ]

00:34:01.120 --> 00:34:03.210
It's fantastic.

00:34:03.210 --> 00:34:04.510
Yes?

00:34:04.510 --> 00:34:06.180
&gt;&gt; So I'm also a college student
and I want to be a writer,

00:34:06.180 --> 00:34:09.720
and I'm particularly interested
mysteries and thrillers.

00:34:09.720 --> 00:34:14.010
So I was wondering if you
had any advice for, like,

00:34:14.010 --> 00:34:16.340
balancing college life
or post-college life

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:18.520
and being a writer
at the same time?

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:19.820
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: Yeah.

00:34:19.820 --> 00:34:21.120
The question is, is how do
I publish my book, Brad?

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:22.420
[ Laughter ]

00:34:22.420 --> 00:34:25.560
No. So it's a good question,
is after college if you want

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:28.810
to pursue a lifestyle as a
writer, what kind of best path,

00:34:28.810 --> 00:34:30.110
any advice, is that right?

00:34:30.110 --> 00:34:32.430
And I can tell you --
I'll tell you mine.

00:34:32.430 --> 00:34:33.730
That's the only story I have.

00:34:33.730 --> 00:34:37.230
And the beautiful part of
writing is there are no rules.

00:34:37.230 --> 00:34:39.150
Everything that anyone tells
you about how to write,

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:40.510
there's someone that
does the exact opposite.

00:34:40.510 --> 00:34:42.930
There's people who plot their
books and do it by outline form,

00:34:42.930 --> 00:34:44.790
there's people who
say, I'm going to see

00:34:44.790 --> 00:34:46.090
where the day takes me.

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:47.390
And both work.

00:34:47.390 --> 00:34:48.690
It's best for you.

00:34:48.690 --> 00:34:49.990
And so the short
answer is you have

00:34:49.990 --> 00:34:51.290
to find what works best for you.

00:34:51.290 --> 00:34:54.820
But for me, I couldn't
afford to go wait tables

00:34:54.820 --> 00:34:57.020
and then write my,
you know, dream novel.

00:34:57.020 --> 00:34:59.000
I had no money.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.570
I had to figure out
how to pay for it.

00:35:01.570 --> 00:35:03.490
So I wound up just
getting a job.

00:35:03.490 --> 00:35:06.210
I worked here in D.C.
I worked at a law firm,

00:35:06.210 --> 00:35:08.010
I was in law school,
I worked at night.

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:10.490
I just always gave
every single night --

00:35:10.490 --> 00:35:12.680
I would come home from
work, I would eat dinner,

00:35:12.680 --> 00:35:15.090
and my rule was is by 8:00,

00:35:15.090 --> 00:35:17.120
no matter what, I
had to be writing.

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:19.030
I wrote from 8:00 to
11:00 every night.

00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:20.400
I took off Friday nights always,

00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:21.930
and then I wrote
all day Saturday,

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:23.990
all day Sunday, the whole days.

00:35:23.990 --> 00:35:25.630
And I did that for a year.

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:27.010
And that's how you
build a novel.

00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:29.310
A novel is like a sand castle

00:35:29.310 --> 00:35:31.590
that you build a grain
of sand at a time.

00:35:31.590 --> 00:35:33.790
You put the first grain
down, you got nothing.

00:35:33.790 --> 00:35:35.090
Chapter one.

00:35:35.090 --> 00:35:36.390
The second grain
down, you got nothing.

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:37.690
But you sit there for a year.

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:39.930
You write a page
every day for a year,

00:35:39.930 --> 00:35:41.230
you will have a novel
by the end.

00:35:41.230 --> 00:35:42.530
It may not be good,
it may not be great,

00:35:42.530 --> 00:35:43.830
but you're going
to have a novel.

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:45.550
So keep going, keep
going, keep going.

00:35:45.550 --> 00:35:47.440
The answer is, is
I had 24 people

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:48.800
who told me to give it up.

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:51.790
It doesn't mean they're
right and I was wrong.

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:54.810
Or I can look back and say,
you know, I was right and wrong

00:35:54.810 --> 00:35:57.170
and ha-ha on them,
look what happened.

00:35:57.170 --> 00:35:58.470
Life is subjective.

00:35:58.470 --> 00:35:59.770
Keep going.

00:35:59.770 --> 00:36:01.970
Don't let anyone
no, just keep going.

00:36:01.970 --> 00:36:03.270
And I can't wait
until you're up here

00:36:03.270 --> 00:36:04.800
and we get to cheer for you.

00:36:04.800 --> 00:36:07.030
[ Laughter ]

00:36:07.030 --> 00:36:08.330
Yes, sir?

00:36:08.330 --> 00:36:09.640
&gt;&gt; What's your writing
process like?

00:36:09.640 --> 00:36:12.480
Do you do it in the
mornings, you work at a desk?

00:36:12.480 --> 00:36:13.780
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: Yeah.

00:36:13.780 --> 00:36:17.040
In terms of process, you know,
for me, I treat it like a job.

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:19.490
I think I write better
at night, but I have kids

00:36:19.490 --> 00:36:20.790
and I don't want to miss them.

00:36:20.790 --> 00:36:23.990
So I'm usually sitting
down by 9:00, 9:30,

00:36:23.990 --> 00:36:25.370
futzing around on the Internet.

00:36:25.370 --> 00:36:29.900
And then I tend to be by 10:00
at least try to be writing.

00:36:29.900 --> 00:36:31.880
I write straight
through until 2:30.

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:33.240
I don't take lunch until 2:30.

00:36:33.240 --> 00:36:35.090
Because the moment I take
lunch, I just get tired

00:36:35.090 --> 00:36:36.390
and I kind of lose it.

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:39.970
So I want to just starve myself
into, you know, going as long

00:36:39.970 --> 00:36:41.550
as I can and getting that
long block of writing.

00:36:41.550 --> 00:36:43.250
And then sometimes
I can come back.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:46.050
When I was in my 20s, I would
aim for eight pages a day.

00:36:46.050 --> 00:36:49.360
When I was in my 30s, I aimed
for about six pages a day.

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:51.840
When I hit my 40s, I was like,

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:54.070
four pages a day
will be awesome.

00:36:54.070 --> 00:36:56.990
And now I'm like, I'm writing
the best two pages every day

00:36:56.990 --> 00:36:59.540
that anyone has ever
seen, or if I can.

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:02.020
So the truth is, is I sit down

00:37:02.020 --> 00:37:04.940
and I read what I wrote the
day before and then I take off

00:37:04.940 --> 00:37:06.240
from there and then
start writing again.

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:07.540
And I can see my
friend Hank is nodding.

00:37:07.540 --> 00:37:09.070
I'm sure many of us do the same.

00:37:09.070 --> 00:37:10.370
&gt;&gt; Thanks.

00:37:10.370 --> 00:37:11.670
I like your haircut, by the way.

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:12.970
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: I was
going to say, I like yours.

00:37:12.970 --> 00:37:14.680
Tip your barbar.

00:37:14.680 --> 00:37:17.130
&gt;&gt; Hi, Brad Meltzer.

00:37:17.130 --> 00:37:20.490
So my question is, I
discovered you in middle school

00:37:20.490 --> 00:37:22.470
through your Ted Talks.

00:37:22.470 --> 00:37:25.030
Well, also through the
History Channel and also

00:37:25.030 --> 00:37:26.380
through your Ted Talks.

00:37:26.380 --> 00:37:30.800
And you mention in your Ted
Talks anyone can enjoy history.

00:37:30.800 --> 00:37:33.990
The person -- you mentioned
if you do a lemonade stand,

00:37:33.990 --> 00:37:35.990
that person can make history.

00:37:35.990 --> 00:37:38.630
And so the idea of --
I love history, too.

00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:42.380
And so the idea of
constantly loving history

00:37:42.380 --> 00:37:45.910
and embracing yourself
in it is so simple,

00:37:45.910 --> 00:37:48.280
but also some students
hate history.

00:37:48.280 --> 00:37:52.410
So how do you, like, balance the
fact that history can be amazing

00:37:52.410 --> 00:37:54.610
but it's also kind
of hard and complex?

00:37:54.610 --> 00:37:55.910
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: Yeah,
no, great question.

00:37:55.910 --> 00:37:57.230
Because I would fail those
students who hate a history.

00:37:57.230 --> 00:37:59.240
[ Laughter ]

00:37:59.240 --> 00:38:00.680
But the real answer is,

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:03.740
is anyone who hates history
just hasn't found the story

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:05.040
they love.

00:38:05.040 --> 00:38:06.340
It's like a good book.

00:38:06.340 --> 00:38:07.640
When people say, I don't like
to read, it's like, no, no,

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:09.660
you just haven't
found your story.

00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:10.960
Let's find it together.

00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:14.300
My friend John Meacham yesterday
said this beautiful idea

00:38:14.300 --> 00:38:16.990
about history is he said, you
know, history is how we learn

00:38:16.990 --> 00:38:19.630
so much about ourselves, but
not by looking down on it

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:21.670
and hating it, and not by
looking up at it and thinking

00:38:21.670 --> 00:38:24.960
that it's perfect in every way,
some kind of concrete statue

00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:27.690
that we must admire and revere.

00:38:27.690 --> 00:38:30.520
The best way to look at history
is dead in the eye, right?

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:31.820
And that's what it is.

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:35.380
To me, you show me that kid who
doesn't like it, and let's find

00:38:35.380 --> 00:38:36.680
out the story that they love.

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:38.560
Tell me their story,
and I'll tell you

00:38:38.560 --> 00:38:39.860
who their hero will be, right?

00:38:39.860 --> 00:38:42.420
You tell me who you are
and -- when you were a kid,

00:38:42.420 --> 00:38:44.340
and I'll tell you who you are.

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:45.640
You tell me who you want to be,

00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:47.390
and I'll tell you
who your hero is.

00:38:47.390 --> 00:38:48.990
And you just got to find
the right story for them.

00:38:48.990 --> 00:38:50.290
So don't give up on them.

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:51.590
Stick with them.

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:52.890
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:38:52.890 --> 00:38:54.190
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: And if
they continue that way,

00:38:54.190 --> 00:38:55.490
totally give up on them.

00:38:55.490 --> 00:38:56.790
[ Laughter ]

00:38:56.790 --> 00:38:58.090
&gt;&gt; I'll never give up on them.

00:38:58.090 --> 00:38:59.390
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: OK, good.

00:38:59.390 --> 00:39:00.690
Thank you.

00:39:00.690 --> 00:39:01.990
We've got a couple more minutes,
but I want to get all --

00:39:01.990 --> 00:39:03.290
these last two questions.

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:04.590
Yes?

00:39:04.590 --> 00:39:05.890
&gt;&gt; Who do you read
for pleasure and why?

00:39:05.890 --> 00:39:07.190
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: Yeah.

00:39:07.190 --> 00:39:08.490
Who do I read for pleasure?

00:39:08.490 --> 00:39:09.790
You know, sometimes --

00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:11.090
my favorite author is actually
this guy named Brad Meltzer.

00:39:11.090 --> 00:39:12.390
[ Laughter ]

00:39:12.390 --> 00:39:13.690
And sometimes I just put
on his TV show and I sit

00:39:13.690 --> 00:39:14.990
with his books, and
I go, oh, Meltzer,

00:39:14.990 --> 00:39:16.290
you've done it again [laughs].

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:21.100
The reality is -- and
the funny part is --

00:39:21.100 --> 00:39:23.700
actually, that's true.

00:39:23.700 --> 00:39:25.000
I do do that.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.450
I mean, again our
TV show is called --

00:39:27.450 --> 00:39:28.750
it's not even Lost History.

00:39:28.750 --> 00:39:30.980
It's called Brad
Meltzer's Lost History.

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:33.500
It's called Brad
Meltzer's Decoded, right?

00:39:33.500 --> 00:39:35.280
Those are the greatest
titles of all time.

00:39:35.280 --> 00:39:37.600
I was like, I said to my wife
the other day, I'm like, honey,

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:39.550
what are we having for Brad
Meltzer's dinner tonight?

00:39:39.550 --> 00:39:41.890
Because yesterday we had
Brad Meltzer's chicken

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:43.660
and tonight I'd like to
have Brad Meltzer's pasta.

00:39:43.660 --> 00:39:45.510
And she was like, you can go
sleep on Brad Meltzer's couch.

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:48.070
[ Laughter ]

00:39:48.070 --> 00:39:50.860
And that's not even a joke.

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:58.280
So I can tell you that
for me, what do I read?

00:39:58.280 --> 00:40:00.060
I read a lot of nonfiction,

00:40:00.060 --> 00:40:02.190
just because of the
nature of work now.

00:40:02.190 --> 00:40:03.490
And I absorb it.

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:05.240
I mean, I'm just trying
to think right now, OK,

00:40:05.240 --> 00:40:07.610
what were the last books
that I've been reading?

00:40:07.610 --> 00:40:10.020
And they were -- I
can't say who it is

00:40:10.020 --> 00:40:11.350
because we don't have
the clearance on it yet,

00:40:11.350 --> 00:40:14.210
but they were the biographies
of the hero that we're doing

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:17.130
at the end of 2019,
just consuming them.

00:40:17.130 --> 00:40:19.710
On the fiction side, I don't
read thrillers anymore.

00:40:19.710 --> 00:40:21.010
I almost never read thrillers

00:40:21.010 --> 00:40:22.540
because all I'm doing
is taking them apart.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:24.570
I'm like a mechanic
in a rental car.

00:40:24.570 --> 00:40:26.970
I'm just trying to figure out
what's wrong with it, right?

00:40:26.970 --> 00:40:28.960
And it's ruining
the ride for me.

00:40:28.960 --> 00:40:32.040
And, you know, even when I watch
a movie, if it's a thriller

00:40:32.040 --> 00:40:33.780
in any way -- I was
watching the movie Looper,

00:40:33.780 --> 00:40:35.570
which is a great movie,
Rian Johnson's movie.

00:40:35.570 --> 00:40:37.600
And I'm sitting there with
my wife, and we're, like,

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:39.550
a half hour into it,
and I'm like, I got it.

00:40:39.550 --> 00:40:43.190
And she's like, do not
ruin this ending for me.

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:44.910
Do not ruin this ending.

00:40:44.910 --> 00:40:46.890
And the movie finishes,
and she turns to me,

00:40:46.890 --> 00:40:48.190
she's like, were you right?

00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:50.010
And I go, my way
is so much better.

00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:51.690
[ Laughter ]

00:40:51.690 --> 00:40:54.630
And that's all I do in a
thriller is I'm just trying

00:40:54.630 --> 00:40:55.930
to figure out the tricks.

00:40:55.930 --> 00:40:57.380
I enjoy it for about
50 pages to 100 pages,

00:40:57.380 --> 00:40:58.890
and then I'm just
taking it apart.

00:40:58.890 --> 00:41:01.060
But what I do read
nonstop and what I have

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:02.830
in my bag right now
are comic books.

00:41:02.830 --> 00:41:04.260
That's what I'm always reading.

00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:06.950
Whether it's Brian Michael
Bendis or Jason Aaron

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:09.770
or Neil Gaiman or anyone
else that's out there.

00:41:09.770 --> 00:41:14.040
That's what I consume on
truly almost a daily basis.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:17.440
And for me that's
-- it's what I love.

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:19.330
And again, I think, you know,

00:41:19.330 --> 00:41:21.800
local writer Tom King is
doing the best Batman stories

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:23.340
that we've seen in a decade.

00:41:23.340 --> 00:41:25.120
And they're still amazing
because they're not

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:27.700
about fighting crime
or anything else,

00:41:27.700 --> 00:41:29.720
but they're about that great
thing that every book has,

00:41:29.720 --> 00:41:31.020
or at least that I
think is a good book --

00:41:31.020 --> 00:41:32.830
but they say something
about us, right?

00:41:32.830 --> 00:41:35.400
That idea that Batman is Batman

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:36.800
because of the death
of his parents.

00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:39.980
And every day that
Batman goes out to fight,

00:41:39.980 --> 00:41:42.170
he knows he's going to fail.

00:41:42.170 --> 00:41:44.050
He knows he's going
out to stop crime.

00:41:44.050 --> 00:41:46.000
He's got to stop, but
he's always going to fail.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:47.300
He's never going to stop crime.

00:41:47.300 --> 00:41:48.600
There's going to be
another crime tomorrow.

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:51.310
And every day he goes out,
he knows he's going to fail,

00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:54.110
but the next day he's got
to try and do it again.

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:55.410
Or Superman.

00:41:55.410 --> 00:41:57.880
To me, the most important part
of the story is not Superman;

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:00.420
the most important part
of the story's Clark Kent.

00:42:00.420 --> 00:42:02.470
Because we're all Clark Kent.

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:04.510
We all know what it's like
to be boring and ordinary

00:42:04.510 --> 00:42:07.300
and wish we could do something
incredibly beyond ourselves.

00:42:07.300 --> 00:42:10.100
Those are the stories I
love, and that's what I read.

00:42:10.100 --> 00:42:11.400
OK, she's telling
me two minutes.

00:42:11.400 --> 00:42:12.700
And we got last question.

00:42:12.700 --> 00:42:14.000
We're going to land
the plane on time.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:15.300
&gt;&gt; What are your taboos, if any?

00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:16.640
What would you never
write about?

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:17.940
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer: What
when I never about?

00:42:17.940 --> 00:42:19.240
I mean, gosh, wow.

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:20.630
I want to give you
a real answer.

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:21.930
Yeah, run that up.

00:42:21.930 --> 00:42:23.230
We'll do it real quick.

00:42:23.230 --> 00:42:24.710
What would I never write about?

00:42:24.710 --> 00:42:26.660
Nothing. I'm just
that much of a --

00:42:26.660 --> 00:42:29.280
I mean, to me, there's
nothing that couldn't --

00:42:29.280 --> 00:42:31.660
you know, I think that --
the only thing I won't write

00:42:31.660 --> 00:42:33.140
about is something
I don't care about.

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:34.970
As long as I care about
it, I'll write about it.

00:42:34.970 --> 00:42:38.670
And I feel like it can bring --
you know, to me I have that --

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:40.190
the X factor in every book is,

00:42:40.190 --> 00:42:41.720
does the writer love
what they're doing?

00:42:41.720 --> 00:42:44.450
And if they do, it
will show on the page.

00:42:44.450 --> 00:42:45.750
Yeah. Last question.

00:42:45.750 --> 00:42:47.050
This better be good.

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:48.350
The whole room is
waiting on you.

00:42:48.350 --> 00:42:49.650
No pressure.

00:42:49.650 --> 00:42:51.330
Just make sure this is
the best question, yes.

00:42:51.330 --> 00:42:52.630
&gt;&gt; In reference to
your new book,

00:42:52.630 --> 00:42:55.540
where did you acquire the
knowledge to write realistically

00:42:55.540 --> 00:42:57.900
from a perspective of a woman?

00:42:57.900 --> 00:42:59.200
&gt;&gt; Brad Meltzer:
Ah, good question.

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:00.770
No, the question is,
you have one of --

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:03.420
the two main characters of
the book are Zig and Nola,

00:43:03.420 --> 00:43:05.320
and where did you get the
perspective of a woman

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:06.620
to try and write that?

00:43:06.620 --> 00:43:08.180
And obviously, it is hard.

00:43:08.180 --> 00:43:10.290
The first time I ever
wrote a woman protagonist,

00:43:10.290 --> 00:43:12.020
I had her go into the bathroom.

00:43:12.020 --> 00:43:14.400
And she was going into court
and she was all nervous,

00:43:14.400 --> 00:43:16.210
so she splashed water
on her face.

00:43:16.210 --> 00:43:17.820
And then she goes
back into the thing.

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:19.120
All the women are
laughing now, right?

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:22.080
And my wife said, you clearly
have never worn makeup.

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:24.140
[ Laughter ]

00:43:24.140 --> 00:43:26.910
And don't even ask when I had
to write the scene and had

00:43:26.910 --> 00:43:28.810
to figure out what women do
with pantyhose when they go

00:43:28.810 --> 00:43:30.110
to the bathroom, right?

00:43:30.110 --> 00:43:31.410
Like, had no idea.

00:43:31.410 --> 00:43:34.720
Like, it was a foreign
language to me.

00:43:34.720 --> 00:43:37.270
What I do is I rely on
my wife and I rely on --

00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:38.820
Sergeant Amy Brown [assumed
spelling] was really helpful

00:43:38.820 --> 00:43:40.120
for this book.

00:43:40.120 --> 00:43:42.460
And she's the actual --
not current, just finished,

00:43:42.460 --> 00:43:46.220
artist in residence for the
military and for the Army.

00:43:46.220 --> 00:43:48.560
And she told me her life story.

00:43:48.560 --> 00:43:50.470
And her life story is
obviously very different

00:43:50.470 --> 00:43:52.380
from the I made up, but
it was her perspective

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:53.970
that I felt like kept me right.

00:43:53.970 --> 00:43:56.490
She was my true north,
and I wrote toward her.

00:43:56.490 --> 00:43:57.790
And it's hard, right?

00:43:57.790 --> 00:43:59.090
Because I didn't live that.

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:00.390
I didn't have that experience.

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:01.690
I'm trying my best.

00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:03.710
OK, with that, as I get
the one-minute sign.

00:44:03.710 --> 00:44:06.340
The most important thing is
what I said at the beginning.

00:44:06.340 --> 00:44:08.400
Thank you, thank you, thank you

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:10.040
for saying screw you
to Dave Eggers today.

00:44:10.040 --> 00:44:12.060
[ Laughter ]

00:44:12.060 --> 00:44:14.050
And thank you for -- seriously,
thank you for coming out here.

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:15.380
This is the hometown
crowd for me.

00:44:15.380 --> 00:44:17.190
This is where I started writing,

00:44:17.190 --> 00:44:19.510
this is where I love
coming back to.

00:44:19.510 --> 00:44:21.660
And anyone who comes out
at 10:00 in the morning

00:44:21.660 --> 00:44:23.280
on a Saturday and
wakes up early,

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:24.850
you're my kind of
people for books.

00:44:24.850 --> 00:44:27.810
So the next writer is my friend,

00:44:27.810 --> 00:44:29.110
Hank [assumed spelling],
who's coming up.

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:31.190
Please stick around, please
stay in this room all day.

00:44:31.190 --> 00:44:32.490
We have sleeping
bags in the back.

00:44:32.490 --> 00:44:33.790
[ Laughter ]

00:44:33.790 --> 00:44:35.740
But thank you for coming here
and for supporting the Library

00:44:35.740 --> 00:44:37.160
of Congress and the
National Book Festival.

00:44:37.160 --> 00:44:38.460
Thanks very much.

00:44:38.460 --> 00:44:39.000
[ Applause ]

